7.1.1 - W11SR14: Ineffective Security Reporting and Compliance Data for Stand-alone Workstations
ISM controls:
•	0013; 0015 (Relating to the security reporting to chief information security officers and service providers).
•	0031; 0032 (Relating to the maintenance of system security plans and security assessment reports).
•	1410; 1471 (Relating to the identification of installed software and configuration management).
•	1494; 1495 (Relating to the identification and reporting of security vulnerabilities).
Current Risk
Due to the periodic disconnected nature of stand-alone workstations, the agency may observe ineffective, inaccurate, or missing reporting and compliance data. This lack of telemetry prevents the effective management and identification of installed software versions, potential vulnerable software, and deployed software counts. This visibility gap leads to an increased attack surface and reduced security control, potentially resulting in a compromise of the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of the agency’s system and its data.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Implement Offline Asset Discovery: Establish a mandatory process for the manual extraction of hardware and software inventories from stand-alone devices using approved, secure tools for ingestion into a centralised asset management database.
•	Standardise Baseline Auditing: Use automated configuration audit scripts (e.g., PowerShell-based CIS or ASD baseline checkers) to generate local compliance reports that are reviewed during every physical maintenance cycle.
•	Vulnerability Register for Stand-alone Assets: Maintain a dedicated, high-fidelity register of software vulnerabilities specifically for disconnected assets, cross-referenced with vendor security advisories to track patching progress.
- Treatment #1
•	Deploy a "System Health Check" utility to every stand-alone workstation that provides a visual compliance status (e.g., green/amber/red) to the user based on the last successful update and scan.
•	Mandate the use of encrypted portable media for the secure transfer of local audit logs to the agency SIEM or reporting portal to ensure data integrity during the "Sneakernet" process.
•	Perform quarterly "Security Posture Validations" where an independent officer verifies that the local system state matches the data recorded in the agency's central asset and compliance registers.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
While the disconnected nature of these systems prevents real-time reporting, the implementation of a structured offline discovery and auditing regime provides the agency with sufficient visibility to manage the attack surface effectively. By formalising the collection of software and vulnerability data, the likelihood of an undetected security gap leading to a compromise is reduced to "Unlikely."
